10:58.733 --> 11:01.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Democratic Senator Mark
Warner today pressed the
attorney general on that.

11:01.533 --> 11:02.533 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Let's listen.

11:02.533 --> 11:04.633 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
®MD-BSEN.

11:04.633 --> 11:07.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARK WARNER (D), Virginia: Mr.
Comey's testimony last week was
that he felt uncomfortable when

11:07.400 --> 11:11.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the president asked everyone
else to leave the room.

11:11.633 --> 11:15.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He left the impression that
you lingered, perhaps a sense
that you felt uncomfortable

11:15.500 --> 11:17.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
about it as well.

11:17.300 --> 11:21.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFF SESSIONS: Well, I
would just say it this way.

11:21.100 --> 11:22.100 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
We were there.

11:22.100 --> 11:24.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I was standing there.

11:24.200 --> 11:29.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And without revealing any
conversation that took place,
what I do recall is that I did

11:30.366 --> 11:32.500 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
depart.

11:32.500 --> 11:36.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I believe everyone else
did depart, and Director
Comey was sitting in
front of the president's

11:37.233 --> 11:38.166 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
desk, and they were talking.

11:38.166 --> 11:40.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, that's what I do remember.

11:40.233 --> 11:44.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I believe it was the
next day that he said
something, expressed
concern about being left

11:45.300 --> 11:46.966 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
alone with the president.

11:46.966 --> 11:51.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But that, in itself,
is not problematic.

11:51.566 --> 11:56.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He didn't tell me, at that time,
any details about anything that
was said that was improper.

11:58.633 --> 12:03.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I affirmed his concern that we
should be following the proper
guidelines of the Department of

12:05.800 --> 12:09.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Justice and basically backed
him up in his concerns.

12:09.366 --> 12:13.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, let's turn
now to our three panelists.

12:13.166 --> 12:15.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Carrie Cordero, I'm
going to start with you.

12:15.200 --> 12:19.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What do you make of that answer
that he really didn't have an
explanation for leaving the

12:19.400 --> 12:23.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
room, whether he thought that
was unusual, leaving the Oval
Office when the president

12:23.366 --> 12:28.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
wanted to be alone with the
then FBI director, and he didn't
seem terribly upset about the

12:30.433 --> 12:32.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
fact that the FBI director
was concerned the next day
when he told him about it?

12:32.533 --> 12:34.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
CARRIE CORDERO, Former
Department of Justice
Official: Right.

12:34.533 --> 12:37.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, these memos that he's
talking about, this longstanding
Department of Justice policy,

12:37.700 --> 12:42.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has to do with, in recent
history, there was a
memo that an Attorney
General Mukasey issued,

12:42.533 --> 12:47.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that Eric Holder issued that
restrict the contacts between
the White House and the Justice

12:49.066 --> 12:51.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Department and the
FBI investigators on
ongoing investigations.

12:51.766 --> 12:56.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so it was still an
odd answer, because, given
the fact that there was
this major investigation

12:58.766 --> 13:02.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
going on that the attorney
general himself knew that he
was recused from, it would be

13:04.233 --> 13:06.233 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
unusual.

13:06.233 --> 13:10.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Why would the president need
to hold back the FBI director
about something that the

13:12.300 --> 13:15.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
attorney general couldn't
be present for, other than
the Russia investigation?

13:15.133 --> 13:20.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In other words, anything else
that the FBI director and the
president needed to discuss

13:22.066 --> 13:24.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of a substantive nature,
one would think the attorney
general could be there for it.

13:24.933 --> 13:27.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: George
Terwilliger, what about that?

13:27.033 --> 13:28.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GEORGE TERWILLIGER, Former U.S.
Deputy Attorney General: Well,
I don't think it's that unusual

13:28.700 --> 13:32.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for a president to talk
to an FBI director alone.

13:32.366 --> 13:37.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think it would probably be
worth asking a number of former
FBI directors if they ever

13:38.700 --> 13:40.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
had one-on-one conversations
with the president.

13:40.733 --> 13:43.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Even in this
-- in the middle of this
kind of an investigation?

13:43.133 --> 13:45.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GEORGE TERWILLIGER: Yes.

13:45.266 --> 13:47.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, I think, in hindsight,
anybody that looks at it would
go, it would have been better

13:47.400 --> 13:52.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for that not to have occurred,
but the fact that the president
asked and the attorney

13:53.766 --> 13:56.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
general -- I just -- I
mean, he's a courteous man.

13:56.200 --> 13:59.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I think he respected
the president's wishes.

13:59.333 --> 14:04.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And more than anything, Judy,
I -- what came through to me
today, more than an attorney

14:04.266 --> 14:08.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
general, was I saw a man who
said, you're not going to
play political football with

14:08.633 --> 14:13.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
my integrity, and said
that very, very firmly
even as to that question.

14:13.133 --> 14:16.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Walter Dellinger,
what did you take away from
the hearing overall, and

14:16.433 --> 14:21.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what about the specific
point about the president
asking everybody to
clear the room while he

14:22.200 --> 14:24.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
talked to James Comey?

14:24.300 --> 14:26.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
®MD-BWALTER DELLINGER, Former
Acting Solicitor General: Well,
I think what was particularly

14:26.366 --> 14:29.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
improper about that conversation
was the content of it, that is,
the president saying, I hope

14:31.166 --> 14:36.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you will end this investigation
into General Flynn.

14:38.100 --> 14:42.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Even if that wasn't a directive,
that statement that you should
end it because he's a good

14:43.933 --> 14:48.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
guy undercuts our basic notion
of equal justice under law.

14:50.766 --> 14:53.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We shouldn't be investigating
or stopping investigations
because the president thinks

14:53.600 --> 14:57.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
someone is a good guy or
a U.S. attorney thinks
someone is a good guy.

14:57.466 --> 14:59.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's number one.

14:59.933 --> 15:03.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My larger takeaway
is that the attorney
general seemed relatively
passionate in defending

15:05.266 --> 15:08.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
his own lack of involvement
with the Russians
and quite convincing.

15:08.500 --> 15:10.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: He did.

15:10.633 --> 15:14.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WALTER DELLINGER: He
showed much less concern
about this extraordinary
event that the Russian,

15:16.333 --> 15:19.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a foreign military
hostile power, tried to
interfere in our elections.

15:19.766 --> 15:24.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He referred to it as
improper, but he didn't seem
to have any energy about
where that investigation

15:26.766 --> 15:29.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
should go, didn't seem to
suggest that the president of
the United States is concerned

15:29.466 --> 15:34.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about what was really a foreign
attack by a hostile power on
the core of our democracy.

15:34.166 --> 15:37.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we have got
a little excerpt of that coming
up, and I want to ask you that.

15:37.133 --> 15:42.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But just quickly, on this point,
Carrie Cordero, again, on --
is there a precedent for the

15:45.066 --> 15:50.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
attorney general basically
saying, it's OK for me to remove
myself from a conversation

15:50.066 --> 15:52.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and let the president talk
to the head of the FBI
about something sensitive?

15:52.900 --> 15:57.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CARRIE CORDERO: Well, so,
in other circumstances,
if, for example, the
FBI director was at the

15:57.866 --> 16:02.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
White House to give a
counterterrorism briefing,
on some really substantive
matter, then, sure.

16:02.700 --> 16:05.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But there would be other
aides in the room, too.

16:05.400 --> 16:10.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That type of briefing wouldn't
take place just with the
president and the FBI director.

16:10.333 --> 16:15.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But those are the types
of scenarios that would
be more routine types
of meetings between

16:17.166 --> 16:20.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a president and an FBI
director, if it was some
substantive type of briefing.

16:20.733 --> 16:24.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, and -- and
keep all that in mind, because
we want to turn to another

16:24.933 --> 16:27.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
aspect of what came out
in today's testimony.

16:27.900 --> 16:32.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is that more
than one senator asked
the attorney general
about the firing of James

16:33.366 --> 16:35.933 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Comey.

16:35.933 --> 16:38.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The attorney general
testified that he didn't
talk to the FBI director
about his job performance

16:38.966 --> 16:41.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
before the president
dismissed him.

16:41.066 --> 16:45.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He did detail for California
Democrat Dianne Feinstein the
issues that he had with Comey,

16:47.566 --> 16:51.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but he declined to answer
a later question from Maine
independent Senator Angus King.

16:51.433 --> 16:54.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFF SESSIONS: We
had problems there.

16:54.700 --> 16:59.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it was my best judgment that
a fresh start at the FBI was
the appropriate thing to do.

17:03.766 --> 17:06.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And when asked, I said
that to president.

17:06.533 --> 17:08.833 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's something I had adhered to.

17:08.833 --> 17:12.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Deputy Rosenstein's letter
dealt with a number of things.

17:12.866 --> 17:17.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When the -- Mr. Comey declined
the Clinton prosecution,
that was really a usurpation

17:22.933 --> 17:27.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the authority of the
federal prosecutors in
the Department of Justice.

17:28.800 --> 17:30.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It was a stunning development.

17:30.766 --> 17:35.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The FBI -- the investigative
team, they don't decide
prosecution policies.

17:37.900 --> 17:41.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that was a thunderous thing.

17:41.033 --> 17:46.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He also commented at some
length on the declination
of the Clinton prosecution,
which you shouldn't

17:49.400 --> 17:50.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
normally -- you shouldn't do.

17:50.900 --> 17:52.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The policies have been historic.

17:52.866 --> 17:55.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If you decline, you decline
and you don't talk about it.

17:55.900 --> 18:00.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There were other things that
had happened that indicated
to me a lack of discipline.

18:02.566 --> 18:06.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it caused controversy
on both sides of the aisle.

18:06.366 --> 18:10.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And I had come to the
conclusion that a fresh
start was appropriate.

18:10.200 --> 18:11.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

18:11.200 --> 18:13.866 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

18:13.866 --> 18:15.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANGUS KING (I), Maine: In
any of your discussions
about the firing of James
Comey, did the question

18:15.166 --> 18:17.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the Russian
investigation ever come up?

18:17.233 --> 18:21.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFF SESSIONS: I cannot
answer that because
it was a communication
by the president, or,

18:23.566 --> 18:27.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
if any such occurred, it
would be a communication
that he has not waived.

18:27.500 --> 18:31.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, a number
of people, George Terwilliger,
were struck by the fact that

18:31.666 --> 18:35.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the attorney general wouldn't
talk about these conversations
he had with the president.

18:35.633 --> 18:40.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GEORGE TERWILLIGER: Well, to
me, that makes perfect sense.

18:40.033 --> 18:45.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The privilege belongs to the
president, and it wouldn't be
up to a subordinate official

18:46.900 --> 18:50.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to take it upon himself to
waive it by answering the
question at that time and place.

18:52.833 --> 18:57.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Otherwise, the president
loses the ability to assert
or preserve that privilege.

18:57.100 --> 19:01.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you
and I were discussing this
earlier, Walter Dellinger.

19:01.233 --> 19:06.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We were trying to understand,
to what extent is there a
precedent for not answering some

19:07.800 --> 19:09.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of these questions?

19:09.900 --> 19:12.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We heard the attorney general
say -- at one point, he said,
I think there's even a piece

19:12.566 --> 19:17.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of paper at the Justice
Department that refers
to privileged or
confidential conversations

19:18.966 --> 19:21.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
between the president
and the attorney general.

19:21.466 --> 19:23.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WALTER DELLINGER: You know,
he was very well-prepared,
but he didn't bring
any such piece of paper

19:23.966 --> 19:26.000 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
with him.

19:26.000 --> 19:29.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I would be surprised,
because I don't believe there
is any privilege of refusing

19:29.833 --> 19:34.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to answer questions from
a congressional committee,
unless the president is
going to invoke executive

19:34.666 --> 19:35.666 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
privilege.

19:35.666 --> 19:37.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And he didn't want to say that.

19:37.733 --> 19:41.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Through a dozen iterations of
the question, he would simply
say, it was confidential,

19:41.800 --> 19:43.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
without asserting any privilege.

19:43.866 --> 19:48.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Finally, he suggested -- and the
committee should follow up on
this -- here are the questions

19:49.100 --> 19:51.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
we want answered.

19:51.200 --> 19:55.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Did you discuss the Russian
investigation in connection
with the firing of Comey?

19:57.100 --> 20:00.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And if the president then wants
to assert executive privilege,
he can do so in writing

20:00.133 --> 20:02.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
communicated to the committee.

20:02.033 --> 20:05.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, if not, then the
question ought to be answered
by the attorney general.

20:05.500 --> 20:08.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Carrie
Cordero, this really does get to
the heart of a lot of what we're

20:08.433 --> 20:13.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
talking about today, and that
is, the president has not so
far exerted executive privilege.

20:15.333 --> 20:17.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He has not said to the
attorney general, you cannot
answer these questions.

20:17.833 --> 20:22.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the attorney general said,
at least on two occasions today,
that he's trying to protect

20:22.800 --> 20:27.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the president's right to
later on exert executive
privilege, which is a
way of looking at this,

20:29.666 --> 20:31.000 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
I think, some of
us haven't seen.

20:31.000 --> 20:33.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
CARRIE CORDERO: Right.

20:33.066 --> 20:37.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, this is the second week in
a row that senior administration
officials have had difficulty

20:37.766 --> 20:39.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
answering this question.

20:39.800 --> 20:44.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DNI Coats, Director of National
Intelligence Coats, and
Director of NSA Rogers last week

20:46.533 --> 20:49.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
had a similar problem,
where they didn't seem
to have been advised by
the White House Counsel's

20:52.166 --> 20:54.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Office that they should
exert executive privilege,
and yet they were
uncomfortable giving answers

20:56.300 --> 20:57.900 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to questions.

20:57.900 --> 21:00.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Attorney General
Sessions handled it a
little bit differently.

21:00.533 --> 21:05.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He did say that he was trying
to protect a potential exertion
of executive privilege,

21:06.700 --> 21:08.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
but he also raised
other privileges.

21:08.233 --> 21:10.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
He said maybe there are
some other privileges.

21:10.400 --> 21:14.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And so that reminded
me a little bit more of
the attorney-client-type
privilege that

21:14.833 --> 21:19.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sometimes the Department of
Justice asserts, but that's
when the Justice Department is

21:21.800 --> 21:26.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
giving legal advice to the
president, and they don't then
want to provide information

21:26.233 --> 21:28.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to Congress.

21:28.300 --> 21:32.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, he was still vague and
unclear about which privileges
he was potentially asserting.

21:34.300 --> 21:36.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And that sounded
like a different question.

21:36.833 --> 21:41.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I'm coming back to
you, George Terwilliger,
to ask, on just how
solid is this ground that

21:43.233 --> 21:46.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the attorney general stands on
when he says, I'm protecting
the president's right to exert

21:46.100 --> 21:47.400 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
executive...

21:47.400 --> 21:49.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
GEORGE TERWILLIGER: I
think it's very solid.

21:49.400 --> 21:52.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And both Democrat and Republican
officials have asserted that
privilege over the years,

21:52.700 --> 21:57.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as recently as in the Obama
administration through
Attorney General Holder.

21:58.866 --> 22:01.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's really quite
simple, I think, Judy.

22:01.066 --> 22:05.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If the president has a privilege
to have confidential discussions
with his advisers, which include

22:08.300 --> 22:12.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Cabinet officials, the
Cabinet officials shouldn't
be the ones to decide the
waive the confidentiality

22:13.266 --> 22:15.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of those communications.

22:15.366 --> 22:19.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And he doesn't know what
questions he is going
to be asked before he
gets up there, to ask

22:19.700 --> 22:23.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
permission ahead of time,
can I talk about this,
can I talk about that?

22:23.166 --> 22:25.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, I think it's just
a very practical issue.

22:25.366 --> 22:29.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, there is
another important part of this,
what came out today in today's

22:29.300 --> 22:31.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
testimony that we
want to look at.

22:31.333 --> 22:35.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that is on the attorney --
on the issue of the attorney
general's recusing himself

22:35.333 --> 22:37.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
from the Russia investigation.

22:37.733 --> 22:42.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Mr. Sessions clashed at
one point with Oregon
Democratic Senator Ron
Wyden, who challenged

22:43.833 --> 22:45.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
him on whether he
adhered to that recusal.

22:45.333 --> 22:47.366 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

22:47.366 --> 22:51.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RON WYDEN (D), Oregon: The
question is, Mr. Comey said that
there were matters with respect

22:52.833 --> 22:57.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to recusal that were problematic
and he couldn't talk about them.

22:57.900 --> 22:59.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What are they?

22:59.200 --> 23:02.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFF SESSIONS: Why
don't you tell me?

23:02.133 --> 23:04.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There are none, Senator Wyden.

23:04.733 --> 23:05.933 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
There are none.

23:05.933 --> 23:10.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I can tell you that
for absolute certainty.

23:10.233 --> 23:15.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is a secret innuendo
being leaked out there about
me, and I don't appreciate it.

23:17.233 --> 23:21.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I have tried to give my
best and truthful answers to any
committee I've appeared before.

23:23.266 --> 23:26.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's really -- people are
suggesting through innuendo that
I have been not honest about

23:30.233 --> 23:32.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
matters, and I've
tried to be honest.

23:32.233 --> 23:34.800 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

23:34.800 --> 23:38.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RON WYDEN: Why did you
sign a letter recommending
the fire -- firing of
Comey, when it violated

23:40.133 --> 23:41.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
your recusal?

23:41.333 --> 23:43.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFF SESSIONS: It didn't
violate my recusal.

23:43.966 --> 23:47.066 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It didn't violate my recusal.

23:47.066 --> 23:49.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That would be answer to that.

23:49.533 --> 23:54.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the letter that I signed
represented my views that had
been formulated for some time.

23:56.033 --> 23:58.166 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

23:58.166 --> 24:01.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RON WYDEN: Mr. Chairman, just
if I can finish, that answer,
in my view, doesn't pass the

24:01.333 --> 24:03.400 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
smell test.

24:03.400 --> 24:07.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Walter
Dellinger, this is getting at
the -- what you heard, the tug

24:09.533 --> 24:13.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and pull about all afternoon,
and that is that letter that
the attorney general signed

24:15.900 --> 24:18.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the deputy attorney
general signed criticizing
then FBI Director Comey
as the grounds for

24:20.866 --> 24:24.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
his dismissal was all about
how he handled the Hillary
Clinton, or largely about how

24:24.600 --> 24:26.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
he handled the Hillary
Clinton e-mail investigation.

24:26.933 --> 24:31.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Later on, the president said he
fired him mainly over Russia,
the Russia investigation.

24:31.333 --> 24:36.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And the attorney general
is basically saying, I
recused myself from the
Russia investigation,

24:37.200 --> 24:39.166 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
but that's not a problem here.

24:39.166 --> 24:41.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WALTER DELLINGER: Well, the
attorney general makes the
point that he's responsible for

24:41.500 --> 24:44.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the entire department, and he
has to make personnel decisions.

24:44.800 --> 24:49.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now, this one got awfully
close to his recusal issue.

24:49.700 --> 24:52.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And maybe he should
have stepped aside.

24:52.100 --> 24:57.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, to me, the most interesting
question that wasn't fully
answered was, were you aware

24:59.133 --> 25:03.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
- - when you sent the letter
to the president recommending
that Comey be fired, were you

25:04.766 --> 25:07.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
aware that the president had
already decided to fire him?

25:07.933 --> 25:12.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And that question, he
-- the answer got evaded
in the back-and-forth.

25:12.100 --> 25:15.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that will be an
interesting question for
someone to follow up with.

25:15.666 --> 25:17.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What is
your take on this exchange?

25:17.633 --> 25:22.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CARRIE CORDERO: Well, the
nut of it is, is, was former
Director Comey fired because of

25:23.100 --> 25:25.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the Russia investigation?

25:25.100 --> 25:28.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The president has said in an
interview that it was, that
Russia is what was on his mind.

25:28.733 --> 25:33.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Attorney General Sessions
is clinging to this argument
that his -- his justification,

25:36.133 --> 25:40.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which is that it was
because of the handling of
the Hillary Clinton case.

25:40.766 --> 25:45.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And because he didn't answer
the one question, which was, in
the context of discussing with

25:47.800 --> 25:51.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the president the firing
of the FBI director,
did you also discuss the
Russia investigation,

25:53.266 --> 25:56.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that was the question that
really needed to be answered
to tie these pieces together.

25:56.000 --> 25:57.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, we don't
have the answer to the question?

25:57.833 --> 26:00.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GEORGE TERWILLIGER: I don't
think he's clinging to anything.

26:00.000 --> 26:04.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's very possible -- I don't
know the answer, but it's very
possible that there could be

26:04.500 --> 26:08.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
two very different reasons
on the part of the president
and the attorney general and

26:08.200 --> 26:12.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the deputy attorney general
for dismissing Mr. Comey.

26:12.533 --> 26:17.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Indeed, I know you may have
to be sort of part of the
Justice family or cognoscenti

26:19.466 --> 26:23.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to appreciate this, but what
Jim Comey did last July in terms
of usurping, as the attorney

26:25.800 --> 26:30.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
general put it, the authority
of the Justice Department to
make a prosecution decision,

26:30.566 --> 26:35.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and then the utter trashing
of Hillary Clinton that he did
along with that, that is so far

26:37.466 --> 26:41.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
outside the mainstream, that
the attorney general said today
that he and Mr. Rosenstein

26:43.466 --> 26:46.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
had been talking about
that for some time and the
need to replace Mr. Comey.

26:48.700 --> 26:52.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The fact that that may have
been, or not, I don't know,
convenient to the president

26:52.433 --> 26:57.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for other reasons is something,
you know, that I'm sure the
Senate will want to explore,

26:59.033 --> 27:01.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
but it doesn't impugn
the attorney general's
integrity at all.

27:01.633 --> 27:05.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But just to
quickly follow up, if the Russia
investigation was any part

27:05.966 --> 27:10.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of the reason for the
president's firing the
FBI director, and the
attorney general was

27:12.366 --> 27:16.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
- - attached himself to that
decision, that wasn't a problem?

27:16.766 --> 27:18.833 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That didn't violate his recusal?

27:18.833 --> 27:23.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GEORGE TERWILLIGER: Well, it
might have if, in fact, you
know, he thought that was the

27:24.566 --> 27:26.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
reason or he acted as
that -- the reason.

27:26.166 --> 27:29.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I think Walter a few minutes
ago made a very good point.

27:29.333 --> 27:34.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The recusal is as to one case
out of thousands in the Justice
Department, albeit an important

27:34.800 --> 27:37.300 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
one.

27:37.300 --> 27:39.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The attorney general
still has a responsibility
to run the department,
not the least of which

27:39.200 --> 27:41.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is to make sure he has the
right people in the top jobs.

27:41.733 --> 27:45.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Just very
quickly, Walter Dellinger,
what is the -- what
the -- do you think we

27:45.700 --> 27:50.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
can get to the bottom of this
question of whether the recusal
was violated in some way?

27:53.100 --> 27:56.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WALTER DELLINGER: I think
we will, because I think
the special counsel,
follow-up hearings

27:58.733 --> 28:02.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are going to say, look, either
the president formally invoke
executive privilege or answer

28:04.300 --> 28:07.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the question about whether you
knew already that the president
made up his mind to fire

28:09.466 --> 28:12.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Comey, and to deal with the
fact that it is extremely
unusual for a president to have

28:14.166 --> 28:18.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
half-a-dozen conversations
with an FBI director directly.

28:20.000 --> 28:23.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Walter Dellinger,
Carrie Cordero, George
Terwilliger, we thank you all.

28:25.300 --> 28:27.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Remarkable day,
another remarkable day.

28:27.266 --> 28:31.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And for more
on the attorney general's
testimony, I'm now joined by the

28:31.966 --> 28:35.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
top Democrat on the House
Intelligence Committee.

28:35.066 --> 28:37.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He is Representative Adam
Schiff of California.

28:37.800 --> 28:40.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Congressman Schiff,
thank you for joining us.

28:40.033 --> 28:44.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I know you paid close
attention to what was said
today by the attorney general.

28:44.800 --> 28:49.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Did you come away with a better
understanding of what has
happened over the last year?

28:50.266 --> 28:51.500 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

28:51.500 --> 28:53.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ADAM SCHIFF (D),
California: I did.

28:53.533 --> 28:57.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what was notable to me was
the degree to which the attorney
general really corroborated

28:59.300 --> 29:01.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what is, I think, the most
significant of the meetings
that James Comey testified.

29:01.566 --> 29:06.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that is, he did corroborate
that there was a meeting of
many people in the Oval Office.

29:09.133 --> 29:12.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And although he didn't say
it was at the president's
instruction, it was
pretty clear that it was.

29:12.300 --> 29:15.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Everyone left the room,
except for James Comey
and the president.

29:15.566 --> 29:19.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the attorney general
acknowledged that he did linger,
that he was one of the last,

29:19.933 --> 29:24.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
if not the last, to leave the
room, and also corroborated
the fact that, the following

29:24.233 --> 29:29.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
day, Director Comey told him he
was essentially uncomfortable
with something that took place

29:29.833 --> 29:31.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in that meeting.

29:31.800 --> 29:35.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That tells me that James Comey's
testimony about that meeting
is far more accurate than

29:37.966 --> 29:41.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the president's statements about
that meeting, because, if there
wasn't something uncomfortable

29:43.533 --> 29:46.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about it, then why did the
director go the next day to
the attorney general and say,

29:46.033 --> 29:48.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
don't leave me alone
again with the president?

29:48.800 --> 29:51.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The other point I would
make, Judy, is the one that
you have been discussing.

29:51.433 --> 29:56.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is, we cannot
accept this non-invocation
of privilege as a reason
to prohibit the Congress

29:59.733 --> 30:04.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from finding out whether the
attorney general wrote a memo
or wrote a letter along with

30:06.766 --> 30:10.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the deputy attorney general to
provide cover or pretext for
a decision they knew was made

30:10.900 --> 30:13.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on other grounds.

30:13.000 --> 30:15.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, I don't know if that's
the case, because he wouldn't
answer, but as it goes to the

30:15.966 --> 30:20.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
very heart of whether
the president sought to
interfere or obstruct
the Russia investigation,

30:20.733 --> 30:25.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we need to use whatever
compulsory process is
necessary to get those answers.

30:25.133 --> 30:28.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we heard
at the end of the meeting --
of the hearing, rather, the

30:28.900 --> 30:33.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
chairman, Richard Burr, Senator
Burr, asked the attorney
general to go back to the White

30:35.900 --> 30:39.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
House to see if there's more
of his communications with the
president and with anyone in the

30:40.566 --> 30:43.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
White House that they can share.

30:43.400 --> 30:47.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Is that something that
you think is likely to
produce some answers?

30:47.233 --> 30:48.233 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

30:48.233 --> 30:49.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ADAM SCHIFF: Well, I don't know.

30:49.233 --> 30:51.366 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I would certainly hope so.

30:51.366 --> 30:54.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I will say this, in light of
the conversation that you just
had with Walter Dellinger and

30:54.366 --> 30:56.533 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
Mr. Terwilliger,
a couple things.

30:56.533 --> 31:01.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
First is, the questions
that were asked of the
attorney general were
all easily anticipated,

31:02.100 --> 31:04.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
so there were no
