or bad, is misleading.

50:20.466 --> 50:23.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VERONIQUE DE RUGY, George
Mason University: It's wrong
to be thinking about the power

50:23.233 --> 50:26.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of the president
in terms of jobs.

50:26.000 --> 50:30.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What is important to think is
how -- what kind of policies
can be put in place to grow

50:30.966 --> 50:35.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the economy, and that,
in theory, creates jobs.

50:38.366 --> 50:41.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Since
he was elected, the
president claims he's
persuaded numerous companies

50:43.933 --> 50:46.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to keep and grow jobs here
in the U.S., but analysts who
have looked at these numbers

50:48.366 --> 50:50.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
say they're not nearly as
clear-cut as the president says.

50:50.666 --> 50:55.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Take the president's claim back
in December that the heating
and cooling companies United

50:55.066 --> 50:59.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Technologies and Carrier would
